It is argued that postprandial plasma glucose level is more reflective of glucose control than fasting plasma glucose, thus this may be more useful for monitoring diabetic patients (
 Shahram and Nargess, 2008; 
 Min Park et al., 2009; 
 Lim et al., 2017). The elevated postprandial glucose level is considered an independent risk factor for the development of macrovascular complications associated with diabetes and impaired glucose tolerance. It is also been linked with cardiovascular complications despite the HbA1c values being in the non-diabetic range (
 Aravind et al., 2015).
